                     --><!-- <li><a class="label" href="/ask" id="ask">Ask me anything!</a></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../intro"><small> - Introduction</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../vowels"><small>- Vowels</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../consonants"><small>- Consonants</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../convo"><small>- Conversational</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../beginner"><small> - Beginner's</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../intermediate"><small> - Intermediate</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../numbers"><small> - Numbers</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../urdu"><small> - Urdu</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../all"><small> - All Lessons</small></a></li><!--  <li class="galleries"><div class="label">Lessons</div><div class="menu-wrap"><ul class="menu"><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intro">Introduction</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/vowels">Vowels</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/consonants">Consonants</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/convo">Conversational</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/beginner">Beginner's Grammar</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intermediate">Intermediate</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/numbers">Numbers</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/urdu">Urdu</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/all">All Lessons</a></li></ul></div></li><li id="search"><div class="label">Search<div class="icon"></div></div><div class="form-wrap"><div class="icon"></div><form action="/search" id="search-form" method="get"><input id="search-field" name="q" onblur="if (this.value == '') {this.value = 'Search tags';}" onfocus="if (this.value == 'Search tags') {this.value = '';}" type="text" value="Search tags" /></form></div></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../legal">Legal</a> </li><li><a class="label" href="../../links">Links</a> </li> 

          </ul></div><div id="posts"><article class="post type-text" id="6113164275"><aside class="metadata not-custom-page"><a class="timestamp" href="lesson-113-compound-verbs-part-1">June 2nd, 2011</a><!--  
                               <a class="note-count" href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/6113164275/lesson-113-compound-verbs-part-1#notes">53 notes</a> --><a class="comment-count" href="lesson-113-compound-verbs-part-1#disqus_thread"></a><script type="text/javascript">
    var disqus_shortname = 'learninghindi';

    (function () {
        var s = document.createElement('script'); s.async = true;
        s.type = 'text/javascript';
        s.src = '//' + disqus_shortname + '.disqus.com/count.js';
        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-113-compound-verbs-part-1">Lesson #113: Compound Verbs Part 1</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Today we&rsquo;re going to begin to learn about a fantastic feature of Hindi grammar known as Compound Verbs. So what are these &lsquo;Compound Verbs&rsquo; and why do we use them? Well basically Compound Verbs are two verbs used together to create a kind of combined meaning. They are very common in both speech and writing and are used to express the manner in which something is or was done. They can literally add a whole new dimension to the meaning of a sentence!&nbsp;</p><p>Let me show you with an example just how powerful these Compound Verbs can be first, then I&rsquo;ll teach you all about them! Are you ready? So we know how to say 'I read a book&rsquo;, (read - in the past tense sense of the word!) using what we learnt in&nbsp;<a href="../2392152114/lesson-83-the-past-tense-for-transitive-verbs">Lesson #83</a>, it&rsquo;s just..</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm61goZztO1qzfx8l.jpg">&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2344;&#2375; &#2325;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;&#2348; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2368; </big></big><em>main ne kitaab parhee<br>&nbsp;</em>- I read a book</p><p>But by simply using a Compound Verb we can change the meaning of this basic sentence quite drastically by saying something like&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm612wsoxA1qzfx8l.jpg">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2344;&#2375; &#2325;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;&#2348; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364; &#2354;&#2368;&nbsp;<br></big></big><em>main ne kitaab parh lee&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;<br>- I read a book to myself</p><p>Or we might say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm61i6a8vW1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2344;&#2375; &#2325;&#2367;&#2340;&#2366;&#2348; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364; &#2342;&#2368;&nbsp;<br></big></big><em>main ne kitaab parh dee&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;<br>- I read a book out loud</p><p>Can you see the differences between the three sentences above? We&rsquo;ve used a different Compound Verb in the last two sentences and it&rsquo;s quite simply and drastically changed the meaning! The Compound Verb has told us how the action, 'the reading&rsquo;, was done. So let&rsquo;s learn a little more about Compound Verbs and see how to use them.&nbsp;</p><p>A Compound Verb is made up of two verbs; the first we call the Main Verb and gives the general meaning and the second is known as the Auxiliary and gives the general manner of the action. We always use the root of the Main Verb (remember that&rsquo;s just it&rsquo;s infinitive form minus the <big><big>&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>naa</em> from the end) and the Auxiliary is conjugated as normal.</p><p>Today we&rsquo;re just going to look at one Auxiliary, <big><big>&#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa. </em><a href="../6179578363/lesson-114-compound-verbs-part-2">In Part 2</a> we&rsquo;ll look at&nbsp;<big><big>&#2354;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>lenaa </em>and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>denaa - </em>which we&rsquo;ve used in the examples above!&nbsp;After that we&rsquo;ll look at some more. So let&rsquo;s get straight to it!</p><p>The verb&nbsp; <big><big>&#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa</em> means 'to go&rsquo;, but when used as an Auxiliary in a Compound Verb gives the general meaning of a completed action. So let me show you some example Compound Verbs using <big><big>&#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa</em> as the Auxiliary with various Main Verbs&hellip;</p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&#2310;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>aanaa</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- To Come &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;<big><big>&#2310; &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>aa jaanaa &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</em> - To Arrive</p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>khaanaa</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; - To Eat &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;<big><big>&#2326;&#2366; &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>khaa jaanaa &nbsp;</em> - To Eat Up</p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&#2346;&#2368;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>peenaa &nbsp; </em>&nbsp;- To Drink &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;<big><big>&#2346;&#2368; &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>pee jaanaa &nbsp; &nbsp;</em> - To Drink Up</p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&#2348;&#2376;&#2336;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>baithnaa&nbsp;</em> - To Sit &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;- &nbsp;<big><big>&#2348;&#2376;&#2336; &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>baith jaanaa</em>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;- To Sit Down</p><p><big><big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&#2361;&#2379;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<em>honaa &nbsp; &nbsp; </em>- To Be &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; - &nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2379; &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366; &nbsp;&nbsp;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ho jaanaa &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</em> - To Become</p><p>Can you make sense of this table? We&rsquo;ve got some Main Verbs on the left with their original meaning and then on the right hand side is their meaning when used as a Compound Verb with <big><big>&#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa</em> as an Auxiliary. Can you see how&nbsp;in each case&nbsp;the new meaning is related but still slightly different to the main verb?&nbsp;</p><p>So are you ready to see some examples? Great!&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm6aidyFWH1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2361;&#2350; &#2348;&#2327;&#2368;&#2330;&#2375; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2348;&#2376;&#2336; &#2327;&#2319;<br></big></big> <em>ham bageeche men baith gae</em><br>&amp;- We sat down in the garden.</p><p>Remember<big><big> &#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa</em> is <a href="../2732486975/lesson-88-irregular-verbs-in-the-past-tense">Irregular in the Past Tense</a>! Can you follow this sentence? We&rsquo;re literally saying 'We garden in sat down&rsquo;, using our Compound Verb we&rsquo;ve just learnt! Ready for another example?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm6av0ee3Y1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2352; &#2361;&#2379; &#2327;&#2312; &#2361;&#2376;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>der ho gaee hai &nbsp;<br>-</em>&nbsp;It has become late.&nbsp;</p><p>Here we&rsquo;ve used the Present Perfect Tense from <a href="../5457387996/lesson-110-the-present-perfect-tense">Lesson #110</a>. In this example we are literally saying 'Lateness has become&rsquo;. The verb agrees with the Feminine word <big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2352;</big></big> <em>der</em> - Lateness / Delay. Following? This phrase is great to use if you&rsquo;re ever with people and want to leave because it&rsquo;s late into night, though many Indians may still insist you stay!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lm6cvlcNvX1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2346;&#2381;&#2352;&#2367;&#2351;&#2306;&#2325;&#2366; &#2328;&#2352; &#2310; &#2327;&#2312; &#2361;&#2376;</big></big> <br><em>priyankaa ghar aa gaee hai </em><br> - Priyanka has returned home</p><p>Ready for a last example with this Auxiliary?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/f82ee2ae64e1eb92e766bf920eeb68d1/tumblr_inline_mnfl556GIv1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2357;&#2367;&#2352;&#2366;&#2335; &#2309;&#2346;&#2344;&#2366; &#2326;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366; &#2326;&#2366; &#2327;&#2351;&#2366;</big></big> <br><em>viraat apnaa khaanaa khaa gayaa </em><br>- Virat ate up his food</p><p>Notice here how we haven&rsquo;t use <big><big>&#2344;&#2375;</big></big> <em>ne</em>. We only use <big><big>&#2344;&#2375;</big></big> when <strong>both</strong> the Main Verb and the Auxiliary need it. So because <big><big>&#2332;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jaanaa</em> doesn&rsquo;t use <big><big>&#2344;&#2375;</big></big> <em>ne</em> we don&rsquo;t use it in this sentence.&nbsp;</p><p>Something else to notice is that we usually use compound verbs in either the Imperative form or in the Past Tense. We <strong>never</strong>&nbsp;use them in the Continuous or Future Tense.&nbsp;</p><p>Have you followed and understood everything today? If not then please feel free to leave a comment or a question in the comments section just below and I&rsquo;ll do my best to help you. Well done for reading all the way down here, it&rsquo;s been quite a long lesson! Now to test your knowledge can you try and translate these three sentences? Why not give a go, leave a comment with your answers!&nbsp;</p><ol><li><big><big>&#2351;&#2361;&#2366;&#2305; &#2348;&#2376;&#2336; &#2332;&#2366;&#2323;</big></big> <em>yahaan baith jaao</em></li><li><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2330;&#2366;&#2351; &#2346;&#2368; &#2327;&#2312;&nbsp;</big></big><em>main caay pee gaee</em></li><li><big><big>&#2357;&#2361; &#2342;&#2360; &#2348;&#2332;&#2375; &#2310; &#2327;&#2351;&#2366;</big></big> <em>voh das baje aa gayaa </em>(<a href="../1222427011/lesson-57-what-time-is-it">Lesson #57</a> may help!)</li></ol><p>So have a go translating these, just leave a comment below! And again be sure to ask if you have any questions.&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../6179578363/lesson-114-compound-verbs-part-2">Next time</a> we look at Compound Verbs, as I said near the start, we&rsquo;ll see two&nbsp;more Auxiliaries <big><big>&#2354;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>lenaa </em>and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2344;&#2366;&nbsp;</big></big><em>denaa</em>!</p><p><a href="../6179578363/lesson-114-compound-verbs-part-2">Compound Verbs Part 2</a>.</p><p><a href="../../intermediate">Back to Intermediate Grammar</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/Compound-Verbs">Compound Verbs</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/grammar">grammar</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/intermediate">intermediate</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/june2011">june2011</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/tense">tense</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/verbs">verbs</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="6113164275" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_6113164275"><iframe id="like_iframe_6113164275" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=6113164275&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=tTeulUb7" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_6113164275"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/6113164275/tTeulUb7" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01092527,5.99908429 L16.0088498,5.99908429 L16.136,9.508 L20.836,4.752 L16.136,0.083 L16.1360004,3.01110845 L2.09985349,3.01110845 C1.50585349,3.01110845 0.979248041,3.44726568 0.979248041,4.45007306 L0.979248041,10.9999998 L3.98376463,8.30993634 L3.98376463,6.89801007 C3.98376463,6.20867902 4.71892527,5.99908429 5.01092527,5.99908429 Z"></path><path d="M17.1420002,13.2800293 C17.1420002,13.5720293 17.022957,14.0490723 16.730957,14.0490723 L4.92919922,14.0490723 L4.92919922,11 L0.5,15.806 L4.92919922,20.5103758 L5.00469971,16.9990234 L18.9700928,16.9990234 C19.5640928,16.9990234 19.9453125,16.4010001 19.9453125,15.8060001 L19.9453125,9.5324707 L17.142,12.203"></p